## 2. Social Changes: Gender Roles, Race Relations, and Demographics

### 2.1 Women’s Roles and Workforce Participation

WWII marked a watershed moment for women’s labor participation. With millions of men enlisted, women entered the workforce in unprecedented numbers, filling roles traditionally held by men, including factory work and military service.

- Female workforce participation rose from 12 million before the war to 18 million by its end, making up about one-third of the labor force ([PBS LearningMedia](https://www.pbslearningmedia.org/resource/ww2-impact/impact-of-world-war-ii-on-the-us-economy-and-workforce/)).
- Women served in the military in non-combat roles, such as the Army and Navy Nurse Corps, WAVES, and the Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASP), with over 400,000 women enlisted ([Yellin, 2012](https://books.google.com/books?id=Our-Mothers-War)).

Despite these advances, many women were expected to return to domestic roles after the war, and the wartime gains in gender equality were partially rolled back during the 1950s. However, the experience planted seeds for future feminist movements ([Goldin, 1989](https://www.nber.org/papers/w3203)).

### 2.2 Racial Dynamics and Civil Rights

The war also catalyzed changes in race relations:

- African Americans served in segregated units and contributed significantly to the war effort, which fueled demands for civil rights at home.
- The "Double Victory" campaign emphasized victory against fascism abroad and racial discrimination domestically.
- President Truman’s 1948 executive order to integrate the military was a direct outcome of wartime experiences ([eNotes](https://www.enotes.com/homework-help/explain-some-ways-wwii-changed-social-cultural-political-179660)).

However, the postwar suburban migration often reinforced racial segregation, as many white Americans moved to suburbs to avoid integrated urban neighborhoods, leading to de facto discrimination and urban decline ([PapersOwl](https://papersowl.com/examples/american-society-after-world-war-ii/)).

### 2.3 Demographic Changes: The Baby Boom and Migration Patterns

The postwar period witnessed a significant population increase known as the "Baby Boom," with approximately 77 million births between 1946 and 1964. This demographic shift had profound social and economic implications, including increased demand for housing, education, and consumer goods ([eNotes](https://www.enotes.com/homework-help/how-did-united-states-change-socially-economically-during-1960s-177673)).

Additionally, the Great Migration of African Americans from the rural South to northern cities continued during and after the war, reshaping urban demographics and labor markets ([Kruse & Sugrue, 2006](https://books.google.com/books?id=Civil-Rights-Movement)).

